                {
                  "id": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3wh2f12s/manifest/annotation/p2",
                  "type": "Annotation",
                  "motivation": "commenting",
                  "body": {
                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "<p><sic>his</sic> highly <sic>esential</sic> as that <hi\n                                                  rend=\"underline\">must</hi> be the first step. To\n                                        begin about there to carry out the object in\n                                        <add>?</add><lb/> then follow the plan of the\n                                                  <sic>Jesuites</sic> which is to<lb/> establish\n                                        posts of communications in every<lb/> district from\n                                                  <placeName>Shanghai</placeName> to the place\n                                                  <sic>wher</sic> our supp<lb/>-osed\n                                                  <sic>Bretherin</sic> are to be found, this is to\n                                        be done by<lb/> feeing<add>?</add> the officer of each\n                                        district then they will<lb/> pass the letters of\n                                                  <sic>corrospondance</sic>, and\n                                        <sic>verry</sic><lb/> probable pass a <sic>foreignor</sic>\n                                        through, as let a <sic>foreignor</sic><lb/> Disguise himself\n                                        ever so much the Chinese can<lb/> Discover him, which if\n                                        such should be the case<lb/> the officer of the district can\n                                        torment him in a most<lb/> Barbarous manner for any length\n                                        of time and<lb/> when he thinks proper he can send him\n                                        back<lb/> through the same districts as he come to his\n                                        first<lb/> starting place, and then the isolated\n                                        Traveller<lb/> cannot have any redress from his\n                                        Government,<lb/> a Little money works wonders among the\n                                        China officials<lb/>\n                                        <sic>therefor</sic> I am still of the same opinion that the<lb/>\n                                        <sic>Obsticals</sic> are to be over come in\n                                        communicating<lb/> with the people of\n                                                  <placeName>Kai-fong-foo</placeName>.</p>\n                              <p rend=\"indent(1)\"><sic>if</sic> the people in the\n                                                  <placeName><sic>atlantic</sic></placeName> are\n                                        going to send<lb/> out a mission and they have confidence\n                                        enough<lb/> in me I should have no objection of being\n                                        one<lb/> of the parties for that mission to\n                                                  <placeName>Shanghai</placeName>, provided<lb/>\n                                        that I was paid for going out there, any persons<lb/> which\n                                        they may send if they should come by way<lb/> of\n                                                  <placeName>California</placeName> I shall be most\n                                        happy to give them<lb/> all the information that lays in my\n                                        power as with<lb/> one hour conversation with them I should\n                                        be able</p>"
                  },
                  "target": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3wh2f12s/canvas/p2"
                }
              ]
